## Special Paths

### Contract Paths

{{if .HasContracts}}
{{range .Contracts}}
- `{{.Path}}`{{if .Description}} - {{.Description}}{{end}}
  - After changes, check producers, consumers, generated clients, server handlers, middleware adapters, and tests.
{{end}}
{{else}}
- No contract paths are explicitly configured.
- Treat `api`, `proto`, `openapi`, `swagger`, `schema`, `types`, `sdk`, and `client` paths or filenames as contract changes.
- Contract changes usually affect at least one producer and one consumer; do not update only one side.
{{end}}

### Shared Paths

{{if .HasShared}}
{{range .Shared}}
- `{{.Path}}`{{if .Description}} - {{.Description}}{{end}}
  - After changes, check every child project that imports, packages, or generates this shared content.
{{end}}
{{else}}
- No shared paths are explicitly configured.
- When touching `pkg`, `common`, `shared`, `lib`, `utils`, or `components`, identify importers or packagers first.
- Stabilize shared APIs before consumer child projects follow.
{{end}}

### Infrastructure Paths

{{if .HasInfra}}
{{range .Infra}}
- `{{.Path}}`{{if .Description}} - {{.Description}}{{end}}
  - After changes, check child projects affected by deployment targets, environment variables, gateway rules, or middleware config.
{{end}}
{{else}}
- No infrastructure paths are explicitly configured.
- When touching `deploy`, `docker`, `k8s`, `helm`, `terraform`, `nginx`, `gateway`, `env`, or `config`, evaluate runtime impact first.
- Infrastructure changes should check startup commands, ports, environment variables, health checks, gateway routes, and CI together.
{{end}}

## Decision Rules

- Path matches one child project only: read that child skill and keep writes inside that child project path.
- Path matches special paths or root scripts: identify covered child projects, then read every affected child skill.
- Filename or content represents interfaces, types, error codes, events, messages, or generation inputs: treat as a contract change.
- Filename or content represents deployment, runtime config, gateway, or middleware: treat as an infrastructure change.
- If ownership is unclear, stop and inspect config before assigning responsibility.
